00:43:01,715 --> 00:43:04,985
First, you can stay connected
to what matters to you most

709
00:43:05,018 --> 00:43:07,087
just by glancing at your wrist,

710
00:43:07,120 --> 00:43:09,656
whether you use
the popular Photos watch face,

711
00:43:09,690 --> 00:43:11,525
or a face with rich complications.

712
00:43:11,558 --> 00:43:14,761
And we're adding four new watch faces
for you to choose from.

713
00:43:14,795 --> 00:43:19,833
The Astronomy face has been remastered to
take advantage of the expansive display,

714
00:43:19,867 --> 00:43:23,303
and shows current cloud coverage
around the world.

715
00:43:23,337 --> 00:43:26,139
The Lunar calendar is used
to observe traditional holidays

716
00:43:26,173 --> 00:43:28,809
and special events in many cultures.

717
00:43:28,842 --> 00:43:32,246
The Lunar watch face celebrates
this thousand-year-old practice

718
00:43:32,279 --> 00:43:35,916
with support for Chinese,
Islamic, and Hebrew calendars.

719
00:43:36,850 --> 00:43:39,620
Play Time, designed by artist Joi Fulton,

720
00:43:39,653 --> 00:43:41,688
features whimsical animated numbers.

721
00:43:41,722 --> 00:43:44,358
You can tap the display
to send them bouncing around,

722
00:43:44,391 --> 00:43:47,361
and when you lower your wrist,
they take a nap.

723
00:43:47,394 --> 00:43:51,598
Finally, Metropolitan highlights
watch typography with a new font

724
00:43:51,632 --> 00:43:55,135
that dynamically stretches
when you rotate the digital crown,

725
00:43:55,169 --> 00:43:57,938
and features
many lovely color combinations.

726
00:43:57,971 --> 00:44:02,543
Rich complications enable you to see
more information in a small space,

727
00:44:02,576 --> 00:44:05,445
and we're bringing these
to more of our watch faces.

728
00:44:06,213 --> 00:44:12,352
watchOS 9 also introduces a refreshed
Siri UI and new banner notifications.

729
00:44:12,386 --> 00:44:16,223
And active apps will be pinned
to the top of the Dock for quick access.

730
00:44:16,256 --> 00:44:19,826
Another way to stay connected
is by listening to the latest stories,

731
00:44:19,860 --> 00:44:21,962
or sharing your favorite content.

732
00:44:21,995 --> 00:44:25,899
With watchOS 9,
the Podcast app allows you to discover

733
00:44:25,933 --> 00:44:30,237
and follow new podcasts
using Search and Listen Now.

734
00:44:30,270 --> 00:44:34,174
And the app is now available to kids
using Family Setup.

735
00:44:34,208 --> 00:44:38,879
For developers, sharing content and
selected images from apps like Outcast

736
00:44:38,912 --> 00:44:43,717
and WeChat is easier with the new
Share Sheet and Photos Picker APIs.

737
00:44:43,750 --> 00:44:47,521
And with CallKit, you can start,
end, or mute VoIP calls from apps

738
00:44:47,554 --> 00:44:50,657
like Webex directly on Apple Watch.

739
00:44:50,691 --> 00:44:54,461
That's some of what's coming
in watchOS 9 to keep you connected.

740
00:44:54,494 --> 00:44:57,865
And now to Craig to tell you
what's coming to keep you active.

741
00:45:02,936 --> 00:45:05,672
Craig Bolton: The Workout app
is one of the most popular apps,

742
00:45:05,706 --> 00:45:09,610
so in watchOS 9,
we're bringing new easy-to-use metrics,

743
00:45:09,643 --> 00:45:14,982
views, and training experiences
inspired by high-performing athletes,

744
00:45:15,015 --> 00:45:17,050
starting with running.

745
00:45:17,084 --> 00:45:19,753
It's a sport that,
no matter what your level,

746
00:45:19,786 --> 00:45:23,190
you can use metrics to better understand
your performance.

747
00:45:23,223 --> 00:45:27,661
And switching up your training
can reduce the chance of getting injured.

748
00:45:27,694 --> 00:45:32,633
The first thing we're doing is adding
three new running form metrics

749
00:45:32,666 --> 00:45:35,068
to track how efficiently you run.

750
00:45:35,102 --> 00:45:38,005
Measuring these from the wrist isn't easy.

751
00:45:38,038 --> 00:45:40,440
Take vertical oscillation for example,

752
00:45:40,474 --> 00:45:44,044
which is a measure of how much
you move up and down.

753
00:45:44,077 --> 00:45:47,748
If it's too high, your energy
might be wasted going up

754
00:45:47,781 --> 00:45:50,117
versus propelling you forward.

755
00:45:50,150 --> 00:45:52,085
In order to capture this from the wrist,

756
00:45:52,119 --> 00:45:54,555
we need to extrapolate your torso movement

757
00:45:54,588 --> 00:45:57,491
from the distinctive style
of your arm swing.

758
00:45:57,524 --> 00:46:00,627
We use machine learning
and sensor fusion–

759
00:46:00,661 --> 00:46:03,730
a combination of accelerometer
and gyroscope–

760
00:46:03,764 --> 00:46:05,866
to isolate your torso movement,

761
00:46:05,899 --> 00:46:09,469
and then measure how much
vertical oscillation is produced.

762
00:46:09,503 --> 00:46:14,208
We use a similar approach to measure
the two other Running Form metrics–

763
00:46:14,241 --> 00:46:17,811
stride length and ground contact time.

764
00:46:17,845 --> 00:46:22,382
These metrics can be added
to new easy-to-read Workout views.

765
00:46:22,416 --> 00:46:25,853
Each Workout view
lets you see more at a glance.

766
00:46:25,886 --> 00:46:28,922
Scroll the digital crown to see new views

767
00:46:28,956 --> 00:46:31,425
for familiar metrics like segments,

768
00:46:31,458 --> 00:46:34,027
splits, and elevation.

769
00:46:34,061 --> 00:46:36,830
And we're introducing heart rate zones

770
00:46:36,864 --> 00:46:39,233
so you can quickly see
what zone you're in

771
00:46:39,266 --> 00:46:44,004
and get a sense of your intensity level
at any point during your workout.

772
00:46:44,037 --> 00:46:46,373
There's also a new custom workout

773
00:46:46,406 --> 00:46:49,076
that you can use
to add structure into your run.

774
00:46:49,109 --> 00:46:53,280
For example, if you are trying
to improve your speed or endurance,

775
00:46:53,313 --> 00:46:56,550
you can create a workout
using distance and time intervals

776
00:46:56,583 --> 00:47:01,221
that include sets of work and recovery
which you can repeat as needed.

777
00:47:01,255 --> 00:47:06,026
You can also add one of the new alerts
to a specific part of your workout–

778
00:47:06,059 --> 00:47:09,062
like one to monitor which heart rate zone
you want to train in

779
00:47:09,096 --> 00:47:11,231
to help keep you on track.

780
00:47:11,265 --> 00:47:14,201
During your run,
these alerts will guide you

781
00:47:14,234 --> 00:47:16,837
with both haptics and voice feedback,

782
00:47:16,870 --> 00:47:20,607
letting you know when to switch
between work and recovery

783
00:47:20,641 --> 00:47:24,545
and when to pick up the pace
if your heart rate falls below

784
00:47:24,578 --> 00:47:26,547
the target zone that you set.

785
00:47:26,580 --> 00:47:29,550
During your run,
you can use the Digital Crown

786
00:47:29,583 --> 00:47:33,587
for additional workout views
like this new power metric.

787
00:47:33,620 --> 00:47:37,191
Running with a power target
can help you go the distance

788
00:47:37,224 --> 00:47:41,295
by keeping your effort in a range
that you can reasonably sustain.

789
00:47:41,328 --> 00:47:45,666
You can even see how this workout
is contributing to your Activity rings.

790
00:47:45,699 --> 00:47:49,136
And if it's a route you do often,
it will be automatically saved

791
00:47:49,169 --> 00:47:53,607
in the Workout app for you to race
against your last or best time.

792
00:47:53,640 --> 00:47:57,778
That way, you can see if all the training
you're doing is paying off.

793
00:47:57,811 --> 00:48:01,348
You can use many of these new features
not just when you're running,

794
00:48:01,381 --> 00:48:04,251
but for many workout types like Hiking,

795
00:48:04,284 --> 00:48:06,820
HIIT, and Functional Strength Training.

796
00:48:06,854 --> 00:48:11,191
And for our triathletes,
there's a new multi-sport workout type

797
00:48:11,225 --> 00:48:15,095
that uses sensor fusion to detect
when you finish one leg of your race

798
00:48:15,128 --> 00:48:17,464
and are transitioning to the next.

799
00:48:17,497 --> 00:48:22,703
So it can automatically switch
between swimming, cycling, and running.

800
00:48:22,736 --> 00:48:28,275
That's just some of what's coming
to the Workout app in watchOS 9.

801
00:48:28,308 --> 00:48:31,879
Since the first Apple Watch,
we've been inspired by the stories

802
00:48:31,912 --> 00:48:37,117
we hear from users who stay motivated
by closing their Activity rings each day.

803
00:48:37,150 --> 00:48:40,487
We also know there are many
iPhone users who want to meet

804
00:48:40,521 --> 00:48:43,590
their fitness goals
but don't yet have an Apple Watch.

805
00:48:43,624 --> 00:48:50,264
So in iOS 16, the Fitness app
will be available to all iPhone users.

806
00:48:50,297 --> 00:48:52,733
Using the iPhone motion sensors,

807
00:48:52,766 --> 00:48:55,135
you can track steps, distance,

808
00:48:55,169 --> 00:48:58,071
flights climbed,
and workouts from your favorite apps,

809
00:48:58,105 --> 00:49:01,775
which can be converted to
an estimation of your active calories

810
00:49:01,808 --> 00:49:04,478
to contribute to your daily Move goal.

811
00:49:04,511 --> 00:49:07,181
You'll also be able to share
your Move ring with friends

812
00:49:07,214 --> 00:49:09,516
and receive coaching tips.

813
00:49:09,550 --> 00:49:13,120
While Apple Watch gives you a picture
of your all-day activity,

814
00:49:13,153 --> 00:49:17,057
we're excited to bring some of
the Fitness app benefits to iPhone users

815
00:49:17,090 --> 00:49:19,693
to get them started
on their fitness journey.

816
00:49:19,726 --> 00:49:24,431
Now, I'll hand it off to Sumbul
to tell you what's coming in watchOS 9

817
00:49:24,464 --> 00:49:26,633
to help keep you healthy.

818
00:49:31,738 --> 00:49:33,774
Sumbul Ahmad Desai:
The Sleep app has helped millions of you

819
00:49:33,807 --> 00:49:36,777
by providing insights
into how much sleep you're getting

820
00:49:36,810 --> 00:49:38,946
along with metrics like heart rate,

821
00:49:38,979 --> 00:49:41,348
respiratory rate, and blood oxygen.

822
00:49:41,381 --> 00:49:47,087
In watchOS 9, you'll be able to learn more
about your sleep with Sleep Stages.

823
00:49:47,120 --> 00:49:50,891
Apple Watch uses signals from
the accelerometer and heart rate sensor

824
00:49:50,924 --> 00:49:53,894
to detect which stage of sleep you're in.

825
00:49:53,927 --> 00:49:56,763
Machine learning models
were trained and validated

826
00:49:56,797 --> 00:50:01,001
against the clinical gold standard
of polysomnography with the largest

827
00:50:01,034 --> 00:50:04,571
and most diverse population
ever studied for a wearable.

828
00:50:04,605 --> 00:50:07,307
You can see how much time
you spent in each stage,

829
00:50:07,341 --> 00:50:09,643
as well as when you might have woken up.

830
00:50:09,676 --> 00:50:12,946
You'll see more details in the Health app
where you'll learn

831
00:50:12,980 --> 00:50:16,083
that each sleep stage–
REM, Core, and Deep–

832
00:50:16,116 --> 00:50:18,485
perform an essential function.

833
00:50:18,519 --> 00:50:22,756
And as you sleep, you're likely to cycle
through these stages multiple times.

834
00:50:22,789 --> 00:50:26,627
Researchers are still looking
into what happens during sleep

835
00:50:26,660 --> 00:50:28,562
and how it impacts your health.

836
00:50:28,595 --> 00:50:31,632
We want to help push forward
the science of sleep,

837
00:50:31,665 --> 00:50:36,136
so Apple Heart and Movement Study
participants will now be able

838
00:50:36,170 --> 00:50:39,573
to contribute sleep stage data
through the Research app.

839
00:50:39,606 --> 00:50:44,745
With the large scale of this study, we are
excited about the potential discoveries.

840
00:50:44,778 --> 00:50:47,347
That's what's new with sleep.

841
00:50:47,381 --> 00:50:51,652
Another area where Apple Watch
has an impact is heart health.

842
00:50:51,685 --> 00:50:55,956
We hear from so many of you who have
received an Atrial Fibrillation alert

843
00:50:55,989 --> 00:50:58,625
and sought potentially-life saving care.

844
00:50:58,659 --> 00:51:03,430
So we also wanted to offer support
once you've been diagnosed.

845
00:51:03,463 --> 00:51:06,133
When living with this condition,
it's important to understand

846
00:51:06,166 --> 00:51:08,969
the time you spend in AFib
because it may relate

847
00:51:09,002 --> 00:51:11,772
to your risk of serious complications,
such as stroke.

848
00:51:11,805 --> 00:51:14,942
watchOS 9 can now track the amount of time

849
00:51:14,975 --> 00:51:19,479
your heart shows signs of this rhythm
with AFib History.

850
00:51:19,513 --> 00:51:21,949
And in the Health app,
you can manage lifestyle factors

851
00:51:21,982 --> 00:51:25,052
that may influence the amount of time
you spend in AFib

852
00:51:25,085 --> 00:51:28,222
like exercise, sleep, and weight.

853
00:51:28,255 --> 00:51:32,326
AFib History even helps you identify
the time of the day or week

854
00:51:32,359 --> 00:51:35,128
when your AFib is most frequent.

855
00:51:35,162 --> 00:51:40,100
You can also share a PDF with your doctor
to facilitate richer conversations.

856
00:51:40,133 --> 00:51:43,036
AFib History
is a first-of-its-kind feature

857
00:51:43,070 --> 00:51:47,574
that uniquely provides insights
into your AFib over the long term.

858
00:51:47,608 --> 00:51:52,546
We expect to receive FDA clearance
for AFib History soon.

859
00:51:52,579 --> 00:51:55,148
Apple Watch makes some
of the more complicated aspects

860
00:51:55,182 --> 00:51:57,050
of your health more intuitive.

861
00:51:57,084 --> 00:52:00,454
And this year, we're tackling
another integral aspect of health

862
00:52:00,487 --> 00:52:04,458
for so many of us–Medications.

863
00:52:04,491 --> 00:52:07,895
Over 50% of people
take prescription medications,

864
00:52:07,928 --> 00:52:11,064
and we wanted to help make it
easier to track, manage,

865
00:52:11,098 --> 00:52:13,967
and understand
the medications that you take.

866
00:52:14,001 --> 00:52:18,672
So in watchOS 9, the Medications app
makes it easy for you to discreetly

867
00:52:18,705 --> 00:52:21,508
and conveniently track your medications,

868
00:52:21,542 --> 00:52:23,977
vitamins, and supplements anytime.

869
00:52:25,078 --> 00:52:27,814
You can log medications
that you might take occasionally

870
00:52:27,848 --> 00:52:30,050
like Cetirizine for allergies.

871
00:52:30,083 --> 00:52:32,986
And you can receive notifications
for medications

872
00:52:33,020 --> 00:52:35,088
that you need to take regularly.

873
00:52:35,122 --> 00:52:39,493
Rich complications on your watch face
can help you stay on top of your schedule.

874
00:52:39,526 --> 00:52:44,198
And of course you can track and manage
your medications in the Health app,

875
00:52:44,231 --> 00:52:47,067
even if you don't have an Apple Watch.

876
00:52:47,100 --> 00:52:48,969
To build your medications list,

877
00:52:49,002 --> 00:52:52,673
start typing the name,
and you'll see suggestions.

878
00:52:52,706 --> 00:52:54,975
We wanted to make
creating the list easier,

879
00:52:55,008 --> 00:52:58,312
especially if you take
multiple medications.

880
00:52:58,345 --> 00:53:03,550
So you can just use your iPhone camera
to scan the label of your medication.

881
00:53:03,584 --> 00:53:05,986
You can create a schedule
to receive reminders

882
00:53:06,019 --> 00:53:10,390
and add custom visuals
to make it easier to remember.

883
00:53:10,424 --> 00:53:14,027
Another important aspect of medications
is drug-drug interactions,

884
00:53:14,061 --> 00:53:16,997
which can make them less effective
or cause side effects.

885
00:53:17,030 --> 00:53:20,801
In the U.S. alone,
drug interactions cause nearly

886
00:53:20,834 --> 00:53:24,638
a quarter of a million
hospitalizations each year.

887
00:53:24,671 --> 00:53:28,442
To help you with this, you'll receive
an alert when you add a new medication

888
00:53:28,475 --> 00:53:30,611
if there is a critical interaction.

889
00:53:30,644 --> 00:53:33,914
We've partnered with Elsevier,
a leading medical publisher,

890
00:53:33,947 --> 00:53:37,317
to provide clinically accurate
and evidence-based information

891
00:53:37,351 --> 00:53:40,254
across the Medications experience.

892
00:53:40,287 --> 00:53:44,124
You'll be able to review critical,
serious, and moderate interactions

893
00:53:44,157 --> 00:53:47,060
as well as interaction factors
like alcohol.

894
00:53:47,094 --> 00:53:49,496
Medications also works
with Health Sharing,

895
00:53:49,530 --> 00:53:52,065
which is updated in iOS 16.

896
00:53:52,099 --> 00:53:54,801
You can now send a family member
an invitation

897
00:53:54,835 --> 00:53:56,803
to share their health data with you.

898
00:53:56,837 --> 00:54:00,774
This is another way that you can support
a loved one on their health journey

899
00:54:00,807 --> 00:54:03,277
and have peace of mind, too.

900
00:54:03,310 --> 00:54:05,179
Now back to Kevin.

901
00:54:08,182 --> 00:54:11,151
Kevin: Your health data is some of
your most personal information,

902
00:54:11,185 --> 00:54:15,556
and privacy is central to how we build
and design features for Apple Watch.

903
00:54:15,589 --> 00:54:17,658
Health data is encrypted on device

904
00:54:17,691 --> 00:54:20,494
and is not shared without
your explicit permission.

905
00:54:20,527 --> 00:54:24,164
You'll also now be periodically reminded
of what health data you're sharing

906
00:54:24,198 --> 00:54:25,832
and who you're sharing it with.

907
00:54:25,866 --> 00:54:28,402
There's so much more in watchOS 9,

908
00:54:28,435 --> 00:54:31,538
including support for six
new keyboard languages,

909
00:54:31,572 --> 00:54:35,576
a new way for developers to connect
their watchOS apps to Apple TV,

910
00:54:35,609 --> 00:54:38,779
and with Family Setup,
kids can now control home devices

911
00:54:38,812 --> 00:54:40,747
right from their wrist.

912
00:54:40,781 --> 00:54:44,484
watchOS is the world's most advanced
wearable operating system,

913
00:54:44,518 --> 00:54:46,653
and watchOS 9 takes it further

914
00:54:46,687 --> 00:54:49,289
with new features
to help you stay connected,

915
00:54:49,323 --> 00:54:50,991
active, and healthy.

916
00:54:51,024 --> 00:54:52,492
Back to Craig.

917
00:54:52,526 --> 00:54:54,928
Craig: I'm so excited for watchOS 9

918
00:54:54,962 --> 00:54:57,831
and can't wait to get it
into the hands of our users.

