01:11:09,002 --> 01:11:10,737
So what should we call it?

1179
01:11:10,771 --> 01:11:13,874
Well, that brings us
to the latest exploits

1180
01:11:13,907 --> 01:11:16,710
of Apple's crack product marketing team.

1181
01:11:16,743 --> 01:11:22,749
They've been absolutely riding high
since their naming coup on M1 and M2,

1182
01:11:22,783 --> 01:11:25,853
and needless to say, they were exhausted.

1183
01:11:25,886 --> 01:11:29,723
But after their requisite three-month
rejuvenation retreat in Monterey,

1184
01:11:29,756 --> 01:11:32,292
with their chakras now
in complete alignment,

1185
01:11:32,326 --> 01:11:35,863
the team once again piled
into their macOS naming microbus

1186
01:11:35,896 --> 01:11:39,032
and wove their way down Highway 1.

1187
01:11:39,066 --> 01:11:42,936
Chasing the vibrant display
of colorful California wildflowers,

1188
01:11:42,970 --> 01:11:44,738
they finally came to rest

1189
01:11:44,771 --> 01:11:48,442
where stunning surf meets lush
alluvial plains,

1190
01:11:48,475 --> 01:11:50,944
in beautiful Ventura.

1191
01:11:50,978 --> 01:11:55,048
macOS Ventura enriches so many
of the ways we use our Macs.

1192
01:11:55,082 --> 01:11:56,717
So let's jump in.

1193
01:11:56,750 --> 01:12:01,855
A key part of the Mac experience
is helping you be productive and creative,

1194
01:12:01,889 --> 01:12:05,759
which can often mean having
a lot of windows open at once.

1195
01:12:05,792 --> 01:12:09,429
And the more you do,
the more overwhelming this can become.

1196
01:12:09,463 --> 01:12:11,632
We all want the perfect mix–

1197
01:12:11,665 --> 01:12:14,301
to focus on our work without distractions

1198
01:12:14,334 --> 01:12:17,204
and to easily move between tasks.

1199
01:12:17,237 --> 01:12:22,042
This year, we have a new way
to automatically keep everything organized

1200
01:12:22,075 --> 01:12:25,112
and give you quick access to your windows.

1201
01:12:25,145 --> 01:12:27,848
It's called Stage Manager.

1202
01:12:27,881 --> 01:12:29,483
Let's see how it works.

1203
01:12:30,617 --> 01:12:33,053
When you're working on the Mac,
it's really easy

1204
01:12:33,086 --> 01:12:36,089
to find yourself
with lots of open windows.

1205
01:12:36,123 --> 01:12:39,726
Now, the Mac has great tools
like Mission Control

1206
01:12:39,760 --> 01:12:42,362
to help you find the window
that you're looking for,

1207
01:12:42,396 --> 01:12:44,097
but with so many open windows,

1208
01:12:44,131 --> 01:12:47,334
it can feel like you never really escape
all the clutter.

1209
01:12:47,367 --> 01:12:51,138
With Stage Manager,
you can focus on the app you're using

1210
01:12:51,171 --> 01:12:53,207
without the distractions,

1211
01:12:53,240 --> 01:12:55,309
and it's easy to get started.

1212
01:12:55,342 --> 01:12:59,813
Let's activate Stage Manager
from Control Center.

1213
01:12:59,847 --> 01:13:04,618
As you see, it automatically arranges
all my windows for me off to the side

1214
01:13:04,651 --> 01:13:08,889
and puts the app I'm currently
working with front and center.

1215
01:13:08,922 --> 01:13:10,624
When I bring forward a different app,

1216
01:13:10,657 --> 01:13:13,594
like clicking on Mail here in the Dock,

1217
01:13:13,627 --> 01:13:15,629
you'll see that it's brought to the stage

1218
01:13:15,662 --> 01:13:18,365
and Safari gracefully moves
over to the left

1219
01:13:18,398 --> 01:13:20,267
with my other recent apps.

1220
01:13:20,300 --> 01:13:23,237
When I click on Safari,
it retakes the stage,

1221
01:13:23,270 --> 01:13:25,205
and Mail moves back to the left.

1222
01:13:25,239 --> 01:13:28,842
You'll notice that for an app
with multiple open windows,

1223
01:13:28,876 --> 01:13:32,713
like Pages here, Stage Manager gathers
all the windows together

1224
01:13:32,746 --> 01:13:34,381
in a single pile.

1225
01:13:34,414 --> 01:13:36,750
When I click, I get the top one,

1226
01:13:36,783 --> 01:13:39,987
and if I want a different window,
I can cycle through them

1227
01:13:40,020 --> 01:13:41,555
just by clicking.

1228
01:13:41,588 --> 01:13:43,457
It's really convenient.

1229
01:13:43,490 --> 01:13:46,360
Of course,
just as you would expect on a Mac,

1230
01:13:46,393 --> 01:13:50,964
I can have overlapping windows and
multiple apps open at the same time too.

1231
01:13:50,998 --> 01:13:53,400
It's really easy to group apps together.

1232
01:13:53,433 --> 01:13:59,506
Here I'll just drag in Notes
and pair it with my Pages window.

1233
01:13:59,540 --> 01:14:02,142
This is so great
when I'm working on projects

1234
01:14:02,176 --> 01:14:03,977
that involve a specific group of windows

1235
01:14:04,011 --> 01:14:07,381
like planning a trip
with these three apps here.

1236
01:14:07,414 --> 01:14:09,850
And if I go back to my previous group,

1237
01:14:09,883 --> 01:14:12,553
Stage Manager keeps my windows arranged

1238
01:14:12,586 --> 01:14:14,454
just as I left them.

1239
01:14:14,488 --> 01:14:16,089
I love working this way.

1240
01:14:16,123 --> 01:14:18,192
Of course, like many Mac users,

1241
01:14:18,225 --> 01:14:21,295
I often want to get at files
on my desktop,

1242
01:14:21,328 --> 01:14:25,165
and with Stage Manager,
we've made that easier than ever.

1243
01:14:25,199 --> 01:14:27,167
I'm working on this Final Cut project,

1244
01:14:27,201 --> 01:14:28,969
and I want to pull in a couple of files.

1245
01:14:29,002 --> 01:14:33,273
With just a click on my desktop,
my windows clear the stage

1246
01:14:33,307 --> 01:14:34,942
and my files are revealed.

1247
01:14:34,975 --> 01:14:38,312
Now I can grab these title graphics

1248
01:14:38,345 --> 01:14:42,449
and drag them over
to my Final Cut window.

1249
01:14:42,482 --> 01:14:44,952
I'll just drop them in right here,

1250
01:14:44,985 --> 01:14:46,720
and boom.

1251
01:14:47,421 --> 01:14:51,992
So that's a quick look at multitasking
with Stage Manager,

1252
01:14:52,025 --> 01:14:56,630
Another part of the Mac experience
that helps you do more is Spotlight.

1253
01:14:56,663 --> 01:15:00,167
This year we have a big update
that delivers a more consistent

1254
01:15:00,200 --> 01:15:03,337
and powerful experience
across our platforms.

1255
01:15:03,370 --> 01:15:06,406
Spotlight is great
for doing all kinds of things,

1256
01:15:06,440 --> 01:15:09,476
like quickly launching an app
or starting a search.

1257
01:15:09,510 --> 01:15:12,479
And now you can peek at a result
in Quick Look

1258
01:15:12,513 --> 01:15:14,581
with a tap on the space bar.

1259
01:15:14,615 --> 01:15:17,618
Spotlight can now also find images
from your photo library,

1260
01:15:17,651 --> 01:15:20,521
across the system, and on the web.

1261
01:15:20,554 --> 01:15:24,791
And using Live Text,
you can search the text inside the image.

1262
01:15:24,825 --> 01:15:28,028
You can also take actions
like starting a timer

1263
01:15:28,061 --> 01:15:30,931
or running a shortcut
right from Spotlight.

1264
01:15:30,964 --> 01:15:33,667
It's also a great way to get information,

1265
01:15:33,700 --> 01:15:37,671
now leveraging the full window
for richer results.

1266
01:15:37,704 --> 01:15:42,242
For musicians, you'll see their albums,
key facts, news, and more.

1267
01:15:42,276 --> 01:15:45,746
It's also great for movies, TV shows,
and actors,

1268
01:15:45,779 --> 01:15:48,582
businesses, and sports.

1269
01:15:48,615 --> 01:15:51,985
Rich results and the ability
to take actions right from Spotlight

1270
01:15:52,019 --> 01:15:55,489
are also coming to iOS and iPadOS.

1271
01:15:55,522 --> 01:15:59,626
Now, speaking of iOS,
we wanted to make Spotlight even easier

1272
01:15:59,660 --> 01:16:01,628
to discover and access,

1273
01:16:01,662 --> 01:16:05,165
so we added it right
to the bottom of the Home Screen.

1274
01:16:05,199 --> 01:16:08,502
With just a tap, you can use Spotlight
to launch an app,

1275
01:16:08,535 --> 01:16:11,338
find a contact, or start a search.

1276
01:16:11,371 --> 01:16:14,441
These updates
make Spotlight more productive,

1277
01:16:14,474 --> 01:16:17,444
helping you find
what you're looking for faster.

1278
01:16:17,477 --> 01:16:22,816
Next, let's turn to an app that many of us
use to communicate every day.

1279
01:16:22,850 --> 01:16:25,519
To take you through it,
here's Darin.

1280
01:16:27,821 --> 01:16:30,891
Darin Adler:
Of course, we're talking about Mail.

1281
01:16:30,924 --> 01:16:33,961
Mail is central to how
so many of us communicate.

1282
01:16:33,994 --> 01:16:37,164
This year, we have great updates
that will help you be more productive,

1283
01:16:37,197 --> 01:16:39,666
starting with some
highly-requested features.

1284
01:16:39,700 --> 01:16:44,338
Undo send lets you pull an email back
a few moments after hitting Send.

1285
01:16:44,371 --> 01:16:48,609
Scheduled send, so your emails arrive
at the perfect moment.

1286
01:16:48,642 --> 01:16:51,912
Follow-up suggestions will automatically
remind you to follow up

1287
01:16:51,945 --> 01:16:54,014
if you haven't received a response.

1288
01:16:54,047 --> 01:16:57,117
And Remind Me makes it easy
to come back to a message

1289
01:16:57,150 --> 01:16:59,019
at a particular date and time.

1290
01:16:59,052 --> 01:17:01,588
Next, let's talk Search.

1291
01:17:01,622 --> 01:17:05,492
This is the biggest overhaul
of Search in Mail we've done in years,

1292
01:17:05,526 --> 01:17:07,995
leveraging the latest
state-of-the-art techniques

1293
01:17:08,028 --> 01:17:10,430
to deliver more accurate
and complete results.

1294
01:17:10,464 --> 01:17:13,567
When you click Search,
you'll see recently shared documents,

1295
01:17:13,600 --> 01:17:16,103
links, and more.

1296
01:17:16,136 --> 01:17:17,471
The moment you start typing,

1297
01:17:17,504 --> 01:17:20,974
with each letter,
you instantly see suggestions.

1298
01:17:21,008 --> 01:17:23,744
If you make a typo,
Search is one step ahead,

1299
01:17:23,777 --> 01:17:26,380
only showing results
for the correct spelling.

1300
01:17:26,413 --> 01:17:29,683
And if Search knows a synonym,
it'll look for that too.

1301
01:17:29,716 --> 01:17:34,855
And all these new features are also coming
to iPadOS and iOS.

1302
01:17:34,888 --> 01:17:36,823
And that's Mail.

1303
01:17:36,857 --> 01:17:41,328
Next up is another app most of us spend
a ton of time in every day:

1304
01:17:41,361 --> 01:17:42,729
Safari.

1305
01:17:42,763 --> 01:17:46,466
With macOS Ventura,
Safari is the world's fastest browser,

1306
01:17:46,500 --> 01:17:50,704
rendering the most complex websites
with incredible speed.

1307
01:17:50,737 --> 01:17:53,574
Safari is the most power-efficient
browser on Mac,

1308
01:17:53,607 --> 01:17:56,510
letting you do more on a single charge
than any other browser.

1309
01:17:56,543 --> 01:18:01,148
And of course, Safari is a trailblazer
in protecting your privacy on the web,

1310
01:18:01,181 --> 01:18:03,450
with features like
Intelligent Tracking Protection

1311
01:18:03,483 --> 01:18:04,918
and Privacy Report.

1312
01:18:04,952 --> 01:18:08,655
Safari has a legacy of introducing
key web technologies

1313
01:18:08,689 --> 01:18:10,824
that elevate the web experience
for everyone.

1314
01:18:10,858 --> 01:18:15,262
Safari's pioneering support for HTML5
transformed the video experience

1315
01:18:15,295 --> 01:18:19,733
on the web, resulting in higher-quality
playback and increased battery life.

1316
01:18:19,766 --> 01:18:23,003
And Safari continues to deliver support
for the latest web technologies

1317
01:18:23,036 --> 01:18:24,671
and standards for web developers,

1318
01:18:24,705 --> 01:18:27,541
including all of these
added in just the last year,

1319
01:18:27,574 --> 01:18:30,978
like more fluid web animations,
new browser extension types,

1320
01:18:31,011 --> 01:18:34,515
and support for
the push notifications standards.

1321
01:18:34,548 --> 01:18:38,919
These enable more immersive
and engaging web content for our users.

1322
01:18:38,952 --> 01:18:42,956
And now Safari has a new way to share
your favorite content with others

1323
01:18:42,990 --> 01:18:45,592
with Shared Tab Groups.

1324
01:18:45,626 --> 01:18:48,262
Whether you're planning a trip
with friends or shopping for a couch

1325
01:18:48,295 --> 01:18:52,099
with your partner,
you can share all the tabs in one place.

1326
01:18:52,132 --> 01:18:55,869
And when they find something great,
they can add tabs too.

1327
01:18:55,903 --> 01:18:59,072
You can see which tabs your friends
are looking at live,

1328
01:18:59,106 --> 01:19:02,476
and using built-in collaboration,
you can easily connect in real time

1329
01:19:02,509 --> 01:19:04,311
over Messages or FaceTime.

1330
01:19:04,344 --> 01:19:07,381
It's so easy to discover the web together.

1331
01:19:07,414 --> 01:19:12,186
And next, we have a new way
to make the web a safer place.

1332
01:19:12,219 --> 01:19:15,856
We rely on passwords
to protect our most private accounts.

1333
01:19:15,889 --> 01:19:19,793
While Safari helps users create
the strongest passwords possible,

1334
01:19:19,826 --> 01:19:23,130
there are still ways
accounts can be compromised.

1335
01:19:23,163 --> 01:19:26,567
Hackers can use social engineering
techniques like phishing

1336
01:19:26,600 --> 01:19:29,570
to trick users into giving up passwords.

1337
01:19:29,603 --> 01:19:31,772
They can also breach a website directly

1338
01:19:31,805 --> 01:19:35,642
to get access to all the passwords
stored on its server.

1339
01:19:35,676 --> 01:19:38,512
That's why we've helped create
a next generation credential

1340
01:19:38,545 --> 01:19:41,348
that's more secure, easier to use,

1341
01:19:41,381 --> 01:19:44,318
and aims to replace passwords for good.

1342
01:19:44,351 --> 01:19:48,422
We call them passkeys.

1343
01:19:48,455 --> 01:19:51,558
Passkeys use powerful
cryptographic techniques

1344
01:19:51,592 --> 01:19:55,262
and the biometrics built into your device
to keep accounts safe.

1345
01:19:55,295 --> 01:19:58,365
To create a passkey, just use TouchID

1346
01:19:58,398 --> 01:20:01,502
or FaceID to authenticate,
and you're done.

1347
01:20:01,535 --> 01:20:04,338
When users create a passkey,
a unique digital key is created

1348
01:20:04,371 --> 01:20:06,740
that only works
for the site it was created for.

1349
01:20:06,773 --> 01:20:08,775
Passkeys can't be phished.

1350
01:20:08,809 --> 01:20:10,811
Since the passkey never leaves
your devices,

1351
01:20:10,844 --> 01:20:14,147
hackers can't trick you into sharing it
on a fake website.

1352
01:20:14,181 --> 01:20:18,385
And passkeys can't be leaked because
nothing secret is kept on a web server.

1353
01:20:18,418 --> 01:20:22,789
We've designed passkeys to work in apps
as easily as they do on the web.

1354
01:20:22,823 --> 01:20:27,461
Passkeys are securely synced across
Apple devices using iCloud Keychain

1355
01:20:27,494 --> 01:20:29,429
and are instantly available on Mac,

1356
01:20:29,463 --> 01:20:33,934
iPhone, iPad, and Apple TV.

1357
01:20:33,967 --> 01:20:35,669
We've been working with industry leaders

1358
01:20:35,702 --> 01:20:38,105
in the FIDO alliance
including Google and Microsoft,

1359
01:20:38,138 --> 01:20:42,142
to ensure that passkeys work seamlessly
cross-platform.

1360
01:20:42,176 --> 01:20:45,412
With a passkey, you'll be able to walk up
to a non-Apple device

1361
01:20:45,445 --> 01:20:49,183
and sign in to a website or app
using just your iPhone.

1362
01:20:49,216 --> 01:20:51,952
The transition away from passwords
will be a journey,

1363
01:20:51,985 --> 01:20:55,722
and we look forward to working with
developers on the password-less future.

1364
01:20:55,756 --> 01:20:57,491
And that's Safari.

1365
01:20:57,524 --> 01:21:00,394
Now back over to you, Craig.

1366
01:21:00,427 --> 01:21:02,796
Craig: We think these updates
to Mail and Safari

1367
01:21:02,829 --> 01:21:05,132
will help you be productive
and browse the web

1368
01:21:05,165 --> 01:21:07,434
in new and safer ways.

1369
01:21:07,467 --> 01:21:11,772
Next, let's have some fun
and talk about gaming.

1370
01:21:11,805 --> 01:21:15,375
We're at a point where two things
are really coming together.

1371
01:21:15,409 --> 01:21:19,213
First, Apple Silicon
has changed everything.

1372
01:21:19,246 --> 01:21:23,650
It's taking the graphics performance
of every new Mac to new heights,

1373
01:21:23,684 --> 01:21:28,322
giving Macs the power to run
the most demanding games, with ease.

1374
01:21:28,355 --> 01:21:31,625
Second,
the Mac is more popular than ever,

1375
01:21:31,658 --> 01:21:36,463
and it's a huge and fast-growing
opportunity for game developers.

1376
01:21:36,496 --> 01:21:41,335
And since we have a unified silicon
architecture spanning from iPhone and iPad

1377
01:21:41,368 --> 01:21:43,637
all the way up to M1 Ultra,

1378
01:21:43,670 --> 01:21:47,841
game developers can scale the quality
and performance of their titles

1379
01:21:47,875 --> 01:21:49,810
across the entire line.

1380
01:21:49,843 --> 01:21:55,148
Another key part of a great gaming
experience is the software that powers it.

1381
01:21:55,182 --> 01:21:58,352
To tell you what's new, here's Jeremy.

1382
01:22:01,722 --> 01:22:03,724
Jeremy Sandmel:
We continue to improve Metal.

1383
01:22:03,757 --> 01:22:06,326
It's the software that powers
hardware-accelerated graphics

1384
01:22:06,360 --> 01:22:07,661
on all our platforms.

1385
01:22:07,694 --> 01:22:11,164
And now, Metal 3 brings
new features that will unleash

1386
01:22:11,198 --> 01:22:14,701
the full potential of Apple Silicon
for years to come.

1387
01:22:14,735 --> 01:22:18,238
Gaming at maximum resolution
and quality looks awesome.

1388
01:22:18,272 --> 01:22:21,508
And to help game developers
increase the performance of realistic

1389
01:22:21,542 --> 01:22:26,013
and immersive graphics,
we're introducing MetalFX Upscaling,

1390
01:22:26,046 --> 01:22:31,418
which enables developers to render rich,
visually complex scenes even faster.

1391
01:22:31,451 --> 01:22:34,855
It works by rendering smaller,
less compute-intensive frames

1392
01:22:34,888 --> 01:22:38,959
and then applies high-quality spatial
upscaling and temporal anti-aliasing.

1393
01:22:38,992 --> 01:22:40,327
And it's so cool.

1394
01:22:40,360 --> 01:22:42,529
No Man's Sky,
coming to Mac later this year,

1395
01:22:42,563 --> 01:22:46,166
will be one of the first games
to use MetalFX Upscaling.

1396
01:22:46,200 --> 01:22:51,605
The frame rate increases, giving you that
responsive feel, and it looks beautiful.

1397
01:22:51,638 --> 01:22:54,274
Another area we're improving
is game loading.

1398
01:22:54,308 --> 01:22:57,978
Games continue to push the boundaries
and appear more realistic than ever before

1399
01:22:58,011 --> 01:23:00,814
by using richer textures
and more geometric detail,

1400
01:23:00,848 --> 01:23:02,649
which can take a while to load.

1401
01:23:02,683 --> 01:23:05,719
So Metal 3 adds a new fast
resource loading API

1402
01:23:05,752 --> 01:23:08,789
that minimizes wait time
by providing a more direct path

1403
01:23:08,822 --> 01:23:11,158
from storage to the unified memory system

1404
01:23:11,191 --> 01:23:14,094
so the GPU can more quickly access
high-quality textures

1405
01:23:14,127 --> 01:23:16,430
and buffers without waiting.

1406
01:23:16,463 --> 01:23:20,100
Metal 3 and Apple Silicon enable
even more immersive visuals,

1407
01:23:20,133 --> 01:23:22,669
faster performance, and quicker loading.

1408
01:23:22,703 --> 01:23:25,939
This really is a new day
for gaming on the Mac.

1409
01:23:25,973 --> 01:23:27,441
But don't take our word for it.

